The return of Tiberius from Rhodes (see on 1. 4, 4) belongs to the same year as the death of Lollius; the passage has therefore been stopped so as to imply that the attention paid to him by Quirinius may have been at an earlier date, probably when the latter appears to have been proconsul of Asia (13.0. 7-3).

1. 7. M. Lollio. This person is praised highly by Horace (Od. 4. 9, 34-44)‚ but is painted in the blackest colours by Velleius and Pliny. On his defeat in Germany, see 1. 10, 3.

1. 8. pravitatis et discordiarum, ‘ perverseness and enmity’ (towards Tiberius himself), or perhaps, as a hendiadys, ‘ perverse enmity.'

1. 9. ut memoravi, c. 22, 3. His childlessness, there mentioned, would explain the great influence here ascribed to him (see c.· 25, 2).

1. 15. maiore praemio vulgaretur, ‘might be published and more liberally rewarded.’ As having speculated on the death of Drusus, he was presumed to have desired it: the offence being somewhat similar to that of consulting astrologers ‘in domum Caesaris ’ (c. 22. 2, etc.).
